Chapter 72: The first Midori/Hibiki chapter. Hibiki realizes Kaoru just isn't that into her and she should give up on her after a cathartic water gun battle with Midori. Girls' Frontline is a gritty girls with guns mobile Tactical SLG for Android, iOS and emulator where the player takes the role of a newly recruited commander in a Private Military Company named Griffin&Kryuger, commanding a force of highly advanced android girls known as Tactical Dolls. You, the commander, are represented by a customisable male or female sprite that can interact with the girls in their dorms.

Self-insert/waifu elements aside, the all girls cast inevitably lends to a range of /u/ elements from cute interactions to unhealthy obsessions. It also has a manga featuring a female commander protagonist and a series of anime shorts, primarily Chinese dubbed with Japanese broadcast following.

Because they all only seem to net one single fragment with the occasional two', 'time': 1670709901, 'resto': 3697955}, {'no': 3841019, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)19:09:10', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>3840972
You want to do the last 3 because they have a chance to drop 2 whole the first 3 don't.', 'time': 1670717350, 'resto': 3697955}, {'no': 3841078, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)21:12:37', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>3840972
>>3841019
Actually, that was some advice being passed around in guides elsewhere but after further testing all of the fragment stages do have a (low) possibility of dropping 2 fragments. There isn't really enough data to say if the later stages do drop more.

Even if there is a minor difference, focusing your fragment searches on fewer dolls has the practical advantage of raising their rarity faster. So until such time that somebody does a large-scale survey or a tool like GFLAlarm gets made that can do data collection, the recommendation on fragments is not to worry about different drop rates between stages.', 'time': 1670724757, 'resto': 3697955}, {'no': 3841287, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)01:48:48', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'What am I supposed to do with my Factory now my Oasis is 100%?', 'time': 1670741328, 'resto': 3697955}, {'no': 3841370, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)04:40:23', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>3841287
Somebody made a guide here which has some good tips:
https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vS4BCWp3DdCNSKpYpkuAWw_lYo11bEdMUSCzBSr3vgYMdQLuZhU_Tpu59b9Mvtni5ULS4B5QMxr3pKX/pub

Basically, only the Supplies Workshop and Extraction Mine make stuff that is more resource-efficient than getting it from somewhere else. The Extraction Mine only makes inputs for the other modules. So you want to focus most of your Factory production on the Supplies Workshop.

(You do of course still keep producing stuff in the other modules, because time-based Factory production is free. However, they're not the most efficient way to spend your Energizer income.)

In the Supplies Workshop, the only two outputs that are fairly efficient are Basic Search Commands (BSCs) and Advanced Algorithm Boosters (AABs). AABs are limited by your Algorithm Fragment supply, so just make them whenever you have fragments available and BSCs when you don't.

Since BSCs consume low-poly data, Extraction Mine can focus on that.

There is no efficiency difference between Gifts in Gifts workshop so any output works fine. Note that Gifts are 5/6 cheaper when bought from the Standard Acquisition supply shop (Diggcoin only, not the Quartz Sand items). Since the shop has limited stock and random selection it doesn't reduce the importance of Factory production.

For Data Encapsulation Center, Skill Material Box is a good source of Skill Samples when you have extra Diggcoin not doing anything. You should stick to producing Skill Pivots when your Diggcoin stock is low. Note that, in terms of cost efficiency, Skill Material Box is about 10x less efficient than just running the Resource Collection stage for getting Skill Samples (Skill Pivots have similar efficiency). So you never want to spend Energizer or use up all your Diggcoin here, just do passive production with extra resources.', 'time': 1670751623, 'resto': 3697955}]

Ryukyu Sword Wind Record light novel written by Aoi Akashiro (the same author who wrote NoWaYu):
https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1Qf9VrwnQAjP5yh7XZKUv3EtqEMYPkpW1
>On a certain day, in August 2017, Asahina Hokuto, third year middle school student of the Heijou Institute, and Inami Suu, first year middle school student of Renpu Girls' School, land at Naha Airport. They are here to participate in an operational test of the newly developed Storm Armor, produced through the collaborative efforts of both the Sword Administration Bureau and United States military. On that same day, another toji arrives in Okinawa: Tsubakuro Yume, sixth year elementary school student of Ayanokouji Martial Arts School. The girls have no knowledge of and share no connection with each other. For now. This is a record of the hidden conflict these girls encounter, caught in a scheme involving the Storm Armor, as Hokuto, Suu, and Yume, as well as the elite guard and Mokusa, cross swords. This story, taking place one year before the events of the anime, is Toji no Miko's first novelization!

Nagori Kachou:
https://mega.nz/file/rro3DJAA#P43-uUzLZekWFthFJnVnClCx-8PoGrDeCaJPVS19ikM
>Half a year has passed since the 'Great Year-End Disaster'. One day, in early summer, Hiyori and Kanami are tasked with a special mission. Without being briefed on its details, they find waiting at their destination the former elite guard, currently the special defense team, Shidou Maki and Konohana Suzuka.
